<title>UK: World drug sales up 6 percent in January - IMS.</title>
<headline>World drug sales up 6 percent in January - IMS.</headline>
<dateline>LONDON 1997-04-03</dateline>
<text>
<p>Pharmaceutical sales in ten of the world's leading markets rose six percent in local currency terms in January from a year earlier, market researcher IMS International said on Thursday.</p>
<p>In dollar terms sales rose 1.4 percent to $13.57 billion.</p>
<p>IMS said the fastest-growing markets in local currency terms were Canada and Spain, up 12 percent, Italy, up 11 percent and Belgium, up ten percent.</p>
<p>Sales in Germany, the largest of the European countries included in the survey, were static in local currency terms.</p>
<p>IMS detailed retail pharmacy sales as follows, in billion dollars, with growth rates in local currency terms.</p>
<p>		  Jan 1997		 Jan 1996	 Percent</p>
<p>								  growth</p>
<p>    U.S.	 5.06		     4.74		 7</p>
<p>    Canada     0.35		     0.31		12</p>
<p>    Germany    1.39		     1.52		 0</p>
<p>    France     1.38		     1.39		 7</p>
<p>    Italy	0.83		     0.74		 11</p>
<p>    UK	   0.64		     0.55		 8</p>
<p>    Spain	0.47		     0.45		 12</p>
<p>    Belgium    0.18		     0.18		 10</p>
<p>    Holland    0.17		     0.18		  2</p>
<p>    Japan	3.11		     3.34		  3</p>
<p>    Total     13.57		    13.38		  6</p>
<p>By therapeutic category, IMS said the strongest growth was seen by anti-infectives, with sales up 15 percent, central nervous system (CNS), up 10 percent, and parasitology, up 13 percent.</p>
<p>IMS detailed the top five therapeutic categories as follows, in billion dollars, with growth rates in local currency terms.</p>
<p>			Jan 1997	   Jan 1996	 Percent</p>
<p>								  growth</p>
<p> Cardiovascular   2.69		 2.70		  4</p>
<p>Alimentary/</p>
<p>    Metabolism    2.16		 2.17		  3</p>
<p> CNS		  1.86		 1.74		 10</p>
<p> Anti-infectives  1.66		 1.51		 15</p>
<p> Respiratory	1.39		 1.36		  5</p>
